[Legionnaires' disease is reportable in the US. Because diseases are usually reported by county of residence, one of the Rockland County cases of legionnaires' disease linked to the South Bronx was unlikely to have been reported among the Bronx County cases.

One of the Rockland County cases that worked at the Chromalloy plant was said in the news report above not to be linked to any source. Nevertheless, the Chromalloy plant was closed down on Fri 8 Aug 2015 and its cooling towers and hot tubs were cleaned. Was legionella isolated from the Chromalloy cooling towers and hot tubs and did the genotypes of any environmental isolates match that of the clinical isolates?

More information from knowledgeable sources on the reported outbreak of legionnaires' disease in Rockland County would be greatly appreciated.

The state of New York can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3577511,4302. Rockland County, with a population of over 300 000 in 2010, is the southernmost county on the west side of the Hudson River in the US state of New York and part of the New York-Newark-Jersey City, NY-NJ-PA Metropolitan Statistical Area. It can be located on the map at http://geology.com/county-map/new-york-county-map.gif. - Mod.ML]
